1. Single Responsibility
2. Open Closed
3. Liskov Substitution
4. Interface Segregation
5. Dependency Inversion

Single Responsibility - A class should have a single responsibility

Eg. A garage class has 3 methods, open gate, close gate and perform service. This violates the single responsibility principle.

We can apply single responsibility by introducing a new interface garage utility. The gated related methods are moved into this utility. And this utility is passed into the garage station via dependency injection. In other cases, if a class is doing too much, we can move the related stuff not really suitable for the class into a new class.

Another example would be that for a UserService class that's responsible for registering user emails. Validate and Send email methods have nothing to do with it. We should instead pass an email service interface to userService.

Open closed - Class should be easily extended without having to change its core implementation. Open for extension, closed for modification.

Eg. A bank account class, with calculate interest method. In this method, we check for specific account type and do the calculation. This means everytime we introduce a new account type, we need to modify this code.

We can introduce an IAccount interface which specifies a CalcInterest() method. And have all the account classes implement this method. This ensures the objects we pass into the method have CalcInterest() method implemented.

Liskov Substitution - how to decide whethers to extend a class or use something else

A simple example, bird is a base class with fly method, we can have pigeon as a derived class, pigeons can flu. Ostrich can't fly, so we shouldn't extend bird class to it.

![https://i.stack.imgur.com/ilxzO.jpg](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If a program is using a base class, then its derived class should able to extend its base without changing their original implementation.

Eg. If Rectangle is a base class which we can set the width and height independently, then square can NOT be a subtype of rectangle. If rectangle is immutable, then square can NOT be a subtype of rectangle.

- TS uses extends for class inheritance and implements for interface. In C# it's ":" for both.

Interface segregation - client shouldn't be forced to implement an interface or depend on methods they don't use.

Eg. We have an interface IOrder which specifies AddToCart and CCProcess methods.

However CCProcess method is not implemented by some class that inherits IOrder.

We can introduce separate interface, eg. IOrder that specifies AddToCart, and IOnlineOrder that specifies CCProcess.

Actual order class would then implement one or both interfaces depending on need.

Dependency Inversion - Inversion of Control

High level modules should depend on abstract (interface), not details of low level modules.

Eg. An example of violation would be a PasswordReminder class (high-level) that depends on MySqlConnection class (low-level). If we change database engine, we would also have to edit the PasswordReminder class, and that would affect open-close principle.

PasswordRemidner should not care about what database your app use, to address it. We can interface an interface with connect method.

We can then have MySqlConnection class implements this db interface.

And now password class can connect to any database, without altering its code. As long as the database class inherits db interface and implements the connect method.
